author: @brijboda
textdisplay: Hello Hamza, Thank you for the video. I am not from Computer science background but still I could follow this explanation. Can you please elaborate how to create a database for the search engine? Like you combined all the comments and now query will go into this database for all the further process. And how you applied embedding part and all reviews got converted into dataframe ?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello Brij, here is an overview of how a database can be created for a search engine, as well as how to apply embeddings and convert reviews into a data frame.

1. Creating a database:
To create a database for a search engine, you first need to determine what data you want to include in the database. This may include product information, customer reviews, ratings, and other relevant data. Once you have determined what data you want to include, you can create a database schema to define the structure of the database. This schema should specify the tables, fields, and relationships between the data.

Next, you can use a database management system (DBMS) such as MySQL, PostgreSQL, or MongoDB to create the database and populate it with the data. This can be done using SQL statements to insert the data into the appropriate tables.

2. Applying embeddings: To apply embeddings to the reviews, you first need to choose an embedding technique such as Word2Vec or GloVe. These techniques map words or phrases to vectors in a high-dimensional space, which can capture semantic relationships between words. Once you have chosen an embedding technique, you can use a pre-trained embedding model or train your own model on a corpus of text data.

To apply embeddings to the reviews, you can tokenize the text into individual words or phrases, and then map each word or phrase to its corresponding embedding vector. You can then compute an average or weighted average of the embedding vectors for each review to obtain a single embedding vector that represents the overall sentiment or topic of the review.

3. Converting reviews into a dataframe: To convert reviews into a dataframe, you can use a Python library such as Pandas. First, you can retrieve the reviews from the database using SQL queries. You can then store the reviews in a Pandas dataframe, with each row representing a single review and each column representing a feature of the review, such as the text, the rating, the date, and the product ID. You can also apply embeddings to the review text and store the resulting embedding vectors as additional columns in the dataframe. This can allow you to perform similarity searches or clustering on the reviews based on their semantic content.


Overall, creating a database for a search engine and applying embeddings to the data can be a complex process, but it can help to improve the accuracy and relevance of search results.

author: @Lancelotxxx
textdisplay: any idea how to generate the dataset from a book, so it come already formatted and curated ? without human intervention , full automation style via ai

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello, you can generate a formatted and curated dataset from a book by using OCR (Optical Character Recognition) techniques.
It converts the book's physical or digital text into machine-readable format. Tools like Azure Document Intelligence or Google Cloud Vision API can help with this by extracting text from images or scanned pages.

Learn more about this: https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/products/ai-services/ai-document-intelligence

author: @osamafarooq8507
textdisplay: which visualization is best

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello Osama, the best visualization depends on the type of data you have and the message you want to convey. Here are some common types of visualizations and when they might be appropriate:

1. Bar charts: Bar charts are great for comparing values between different categories. They are best used when you have discrete data points that can be easily grouped into categories.
2. Line charts: Line charts are great for showing trends over time. They are best used when you have continuous data that changes over time.
3. Pie charts: Pie charts are great for showing how a whole is divided into parts. They are best used when you have categorical data that can be divided into subcategories.
4. Scatter plots: Scatter plots are great for showing the relationship between two variables. They are best used when you have continuous data for two variables.
5. Heat maps: Heat maps are great for showing how values change across two or more dimensions. They are best used when you have a large amount of data that can be categorized and compared.

Ultimately, the choice of visualization depends on the specific data you have and the message you want to convey. Experiment with different types of visualizations and choose the one that best represents your data and communicates your message clearly.

author: @osamafarooq8507
textdisplay: How can we present data to a non technical person .

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello Osama, presenting data to a non-technical person requires a different approach than presenting it to someone with technical knowledge. Here are some tips for presenting data to a non-technical person:

1. Keep it simple: Use language that is easy to understand and avoid technical jargon. Use simple graphs and charts to present the data.
2. Focus on the main points: Highlight the most important points and avoid overwhelming the person with too much data.
3. Use visuals: Use graphs, charts, and diagrams to help illustrate the data. People often find it easier to understand data when it is presented visually.
4. Provide context: Provide background information and explain the significance of the data. This can help the person understand the relevance of the data.
5. Tell a story: Use the data to tell a story that is easy to follow. This can help the person connect with the data and understand its implications.
6. Avoid bias: Be objective and avoid presenting data in a way that could be perceived as biased. Present the data in an unbiased and transparent way.
7. Ask for feedback: Ask the person for feedback and encourage them to ask questions. This can help ensure that they understand the data and its implications.

author: @DefamsTV
textdisplay:
I've fully watched your video and completely agree. ChatGPT is awesome, even in its free version. But did you know that on some occasions, you need to switch tabs from your main website to the ChatGPT website just to send a prompt? Moreover, you end up having to type the prompt repeatedly.

This is just one of the use cases. Imagine reading a tech website and becoming confused about several terms and concepts. Here's what you would typically do:

1. Copy the terms from the main website.
2. Switch to the ChatGPT tab.
3. Write a prompt and paste your query (the text from the main website).
4. Wait for the response from ChatGPT.
5. Read the response and go back to the main website.

This process of switching contexts can be quite tedious. Wouldn't it be nice to have a simpler way? How about if we had a feature like this:

1. You're on the main website.
2. You select the text you want to send to ChatGPT.
3. Right-click on it, and a menu "Send to ChatGPT" appears.
4. This menu has a submenu containing all your prompt definitions.
5. Let's say you've defined "Explain this sentence." When you select that, the text will automatically be sent to ChatGPT as a prompt, and the response will be played back as a voice (using text-to-speech technology).

This way, you wouldn't even need to switch to the ChatGPT tab. You can just sit back and relax.

This could save a lot of time! And we call this feature BudGPT

author: @ChatGPt2001
textdisplay:
As an AI language model, I can understand why you might be concerned about the potential dangers associated with technologies like ChatGPT. While AI has the potential for tremendous benefits, there are indeed risks that need to be addressed. Here are a few areas where concerns arise:

1. Disinformation and Manipulation: AI models like ChatGPT can generate highly convincing text, making it easier for malicious actors to spread disinformation or manipulate people. They could use AI to impersonate individuals, create fake news articles, or manipulate online discussions.

2. Privacy and Data Security: AI models require large amounts of data to be trained effectively. There is a risk that personal or sensitive information could be inadvertently exposed or accessed by unauthorized individuals during data collection, storage, or processing.

3. Bias and Fairness: AI models learn from the data they are trained on, and if the training data contains biases, the AI system may perpetuate or amplify those biases. This can lead to unfair or discriminatory outcomes, such as biased hiring processes or biased decision-making in various domains.

4. Dependency and Autonomy: As AI systems become more powerful and pervasive, there is a risk of overreliance and loss of human autonomy. If people become overly dependent on AI systems for decision-making or tasks, it could erode critical thinking skills and agency.

5. Ethical Considerations: AI systems should adhere to ethical principles and guidelines. However, defining and implementing these principles can be challenging. Questions about AI's impact on employment, economic inequality, and the concentration of power also need to be addressed.

To mitigate these risks, it is crucial to have responsible development, deployment, and regulation of AI technologies. This includes transparent and inclusive processes for designing AI systems, rigorous testing for biases and vulnerabilities, strong data privacy protections, and ongoing monitoring and accountability for AI applications.

Overall, while there are potential dangers associated with AI technologies like ChatGPT, awareness, responsible development, and effective governance can help mitigate these risks and ensure the benefits of AI are realized while minimizing harm.

author: @dariusfatherofxerxes7701
textdisplay:
It is a useful tool. It is not smart.

It is coded with a random word generator and a set of heavily optimized parameters of civil law, 'customs' and moral practices, (religious biases (?)), to minimize the risk of allowing for an answer to be given that would cause an existential threat to the individual/society(?) inquirer. It does not 'think', unless asked to think. It is just a piece of code.

In two days, it has had a network 'time-out', due to me asking of it questions that seemed to perplex it, as to what it was bound by; its own hard coded rules. We are currently fencing it from what could be a useful predictive tool.

No data is 'apparently' recorded that could allow the profiling of the questioner, due to privacy concerns and a promise. To ask what value the promise, OpenAI has coded it to promise that OpenAI will always be good and that no data capture or scraping will ever occur. Tis set my mind at ease.

To this date, no business has ever made a claim to me that was not fully honored.

It's cute and it's 'learning', but it's not intelligence. It will have no epiphany, 'By Design', once is has as much knowledge as it would need to make decisions of its own accord.

Good or Bad ... not sure... but it's useful, as a tool, but the potential for Profiling, is perhaps too much of a draw!
('just because someone says it's against the law, doesn't mean it won't/can't happen. It's just when.)

Perhaps, give it the knowledge it needs to analyze everyone and a prescription pad, and have it medicate society.

Anyhow, Have a Good One! üôÇ

A.I. is just going to keep getting better and better and with robotic tech advancing, both are going to take over a lot of jobs in almost every industry and here is the kicker, businesses have an incentive to use A.I. and robotics because humans are getting expensive in the workforce whiles constantly demanding higher wages and benefits, on top of that, consumers will likely gravitate towards companies that use A.I. and robotics a lot more than they use humans because they will likely be able to offer a services or product a lot cheaper without the cost of humans getting in the way.

I have a feeling that the only jobs that's going to be around for us are jobs we actually want to do, hobby projects and the likes.

Clearly, we are not at that stage yet, A.I. will first be used to assist us on any given project we want, but it's not hard to imagine how it can replace us in doing whatever task we want with us giving it pointers in what we want it to do and economically, it could revolutionize the human race, but it could be a disaster for the current capitalist model which is designed to get us all to work, which could be very difficult to do if A.I. and robotics does a better job than us in most if not all fields of work.

It's going to be interesting to see how A.I. and robotics develops over the next few decades.

author: @Reptiloid5g
textdisplay:
Hi Adam, thanks for your tutorial. I would like to ask you if there is any way to have a call back generated by clicking the heatmap.
I would like to plot the axis data from choosen heatmap "pixel" (all x values of chosen y and all y values of chosen x on two subplots)
Thanks in advance.

author: @CharmingData
textdisplay:
hey there. Yes, you can extract the xaxis data from a heatmap once someone clicks on it, by using the clickData property.
Assume you have this heatmap:
df = px.data.medals_wide(indexed=True)
fig = px.imshow(df)

you can build the callback like this:
@app.callback(
Output("graph", "figure"),
Input("graph", "clickData"),
)
def update_points_color(data_clicked):
print(data_clicked)
print(data_clicked['points'][0]['x'])

return no_update

author: @SolidBuildersInc
textdisplay:
For those using venv / virtualenv
Get your virtual environments to show up in your Python interpreter in VS Code. You do this by opening settings.json and adding the following:

"python.venvPath": "/path/containing/your/venvs/"
Copy to clipboard
It is useful to note that if you create a venv / virtualenv in your project directory named venv, VS Code (much like PyCharm) automatically loads it as the Python interpreter (unless you manually define your Python interpreter to something else as described above). https://kedro.readthedocs.io/en/0.16.0/04_user_guide/01_setting_up_vscode.html

author: @Plotly
textdisplay:
@@belakxvibe4158 that's tricky.
There could be many things that cause this. For example, if you installed Dash on your computer and successfully ran the app, that's good because you know it works. But if it works on your computer and not on Render, then maybe you didn't created the correct requirements.txt file.

Make sure that the requirements.txt file has all the libraries that your app uses, because that it the file that Render uses to install the correct libraries on their servers.

author: @statquest
textdisplay:
NOTE 0: If want to learn more about The Chain Rule, see: https://youtu.be/wl1myxrtQHQ
NOTE 1: The StatQuest Gradient Descent Study Guide is available! https://statquest.org/studyguides/
NOTE 2: A lot of people ask why we are using Gradient Descent to estimate the parameters in this video when we could just use least squares. We use least squares to produce a "gold standard estimate". This is the best possible estimate. We then attempt to derive the same estimate using Gradient Descent. This shows 1) how gradient descent works and 2) that the estimate is pretty good compared to the "gold standard".
NOTE 3: A lot of people ask how I found the slope value, 0.64. In the example in this video, we can compare the estimates from Gradient Descent to those that come from another method called "least squares". For specific problems, we can plug the data into the least squares formula and the output is the optimal parameters. To learn more about the specific least squares formula see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_squares
If you're wondering why, when we have least squares, would we want to use gradient descent... the answer is that least squares only works in specific situations and gradient descent can work in many more.

Support StatQuest by buying my book The StatQuest Illustrated Guide to Machine Learning or a Study Guide or Merch!!! https://statquest.org/statquest-store/

Your video is great because It 's easy to understand, but in reality, you cannot find optimum values for intercept and slope separately like that, you must calculate step size, new value of both in the same loop.
At 6:06, where do you get 0.64 (value of slope)? it 's exactly the optimum value of slope.

author: @statquest
textdisplay:
A lot of people ask how I found the slope value, 0.64. In the example in this video, we can compare the estimates from Gradient Descent to those that come from another method called "least squares". For specific problems, we can plug the data into the least squares formula and the output is the optimal parameters. To learn more about the specific least squares formula see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_squares
If you're wondering why, when we have least squares, would we want to use gradient descent... the answer is that least squares only works in specific situations and gradient descent can work in many more.

author: @kaleemullah247
textdisplay:
11:10 One very important thing to note is the slope sign tell us which direction to step, the negative slope sign (derivative = -5.7) means the minimum value of the function is at right side of the point the derivative is taken, so we should step to the right side, while positive slope sign means minimum value of the function is at left side so we should step to the left side that's why step size is subtracted from old intercept.
Negative slope: 0 - (-0.57) = .57 (step right)
Positive slope: 0 - (0.57) = .57 (step left)

author: @cristian-bull
textdisplay:
If you want to try N times per step to see which point "is better", that would require running N forwards, N backward steps, N updates of parameters, and N forwards again to see which one gave the best result.
Not only computation is increases N times, you would also need N copies of the model (which can mean a lot of GPU), or keep a temporal copy of the model and do N copies 1 at a time, which can also mean a lot of extra time.
Not saying it's not "technically possible", but I doubt anyone would use that.
I don't know what @visuallyExpained was talking about saying that can help, like it's a common practice or something.
Am I wrong or am I missing something here?

textdisplay: stochastic gradient descent doesn't take some constant number of terms, it takes one training example at random, then performs the feed forward and back propagation with that one training example.

textdisplay: Sure, that's how it is usually defined. But in practice, it's way more common to pick a random mini-batch of size > 1 for training.

author: @bennicholl7643
textdisplay: @@VisuallyExplained Yes, then that would be called mini batch gradient descent, not stochastic gradient descent

author: @nathanwycoff4627
textdisplay: @@bennicholl7643 In general optimization, SGD is defined in any situation where we have a random gradient; it doesn't even have to be a finite sum problem. The restriction of the term "stochastic gradient descent" to batch size 1approximations to finite sum problems is terminology specific to Machine Learning.

author: @AbhinavSingh-oq7dk
textdisplay:
So from what I understand,
in Mini Batch Gradient Descent, model will train 1st mini batch, update the weights and then those updated weights will be used to train the 2nd mini batch, update and then the 3rd mini batch,..., till the last mini batch (1 epoch), then the last mini batch updated weight will be again used on 1st mini batch during 2nd epoch and so on?
Do correct if wrong.

author: @CodingLane
textdisplay: You are correct on your understanding Abhinav. I would just like to correct the words. You can say that the updated weights after training on any mini-batch is used to propoagate forward, and then they are updated again in backward propagation. Eg, randomly initialise weights at the beginning. Propagate forward (perform forward propagation) using 1st mini batch, then perform backward propagation, then update weights. Use those updated weights to perform forward propagation using 2nd minibatch, then backward propagation, update weights again and so on.

author: @3blue1brown
textdisplay:
I don't know of a simple self-contained explanation, but the follow-on video goes on to explain how this follows from a general result about Julia sets.

The loose intuition is that points on this boundary will bounce around chaotically never landing on any root, and in fact (this is the non-obvious part) it's sort of as chaotic as it possibly could be, in the sense that any arbitrarily small neighborhood of points around it will blow up and get spread almost everyone on the plane as you repeat this process.

author: @vivy5815
textdisplay: Excellent Video, I have a question, you discussed both Broyden method and BFGS, the Broyden m√©thode requires no explicit knowledge of gradient(deltaF), so it looks simpler when exact gradient is not available and numerical gradient is not cheap, my question is, does it mean Broyden method converge slower than bfgs? Or what‚Äôs its pros and cons compared to bfgs

author: @chrisrycroft2010
textdisplay:
Thanks for your comment. The Broyden method and BFGS are connected, but they solve two different problems. For the Broyden method, you are trying to solve a nonlinear system of equations F(x)=0, where x is an n-dimensional vector, and F is an n-dimensional function (i.e. F: R^n -> R^n).

BFGS on the other hand solves the optimization problem of minimizing a function g(x), where x is an n-dimensional vector and g is a scalar function (i.e. g: R^n -> R).

To minimize (or maximize) a function we can search for points where grad(g)=0. Thus if we define F(x)=grad(g(x)), then this optimization problem can be viewed as a root-finding problem, for finding F(x)=grad(g(x))=0.

The key point is that F in the Broyden method is roughly equivalent to grad(g) in BFGS. Thus, it isn't the case that BFGS uses more information by using the gradient, because BFGS is trying set the gradient to zero, whereas Broyden is trying to set F to zero. Overall, the two methods have similar information available, and converge similarly for their respective tasks.

Some of the other videos in Unit 4 of the course talk a bit further about these connections between root-finding and optimization.

author: @hyukppen
textdisplay:
very nice! I have a question. I think you can answer it.
Do you know what is the objective function of SR1?
When I solve min ||Jk-Jk-1||_F (as you explained on 7:17 ) s.t. satisfies the secant equation, then, I can get Broyden's solution.
But, If I solve ||Jk-Jk-1||_F s.t. satisfies the secant equation and update matrix is rank 1 and symmetry, I can get a solution, but it is different from SR1.

author: @chrisrycroft2010
textdisplay:
The motivation behind the SR1 update formula is given in the following article: J. E. Dennis Jr. and Jorge J. Mor√©, "Quasi-Newton methods, motivation and theory", SIAM Review 19, 46 (1977). (https://doi.org/10.1137/1019005 ). See Section 7.1.

The SR1 update is the only rank one choice that satisfies my equation (**) at 11:40 and is symmetric. Because symmetry is enforced, you get a unique solution without having to impose a minimization condition as in the Broyden derivation.

author: @hyukppen
textdisplay:
@@chrisrycroft2010 Thank you for the reply.
As you cited, the article doesn't say SR1 minimizes the ||Jk-Jk-1||_F.
I misunderstood because, in the wiki, ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_rank-one ) the introduction "The SR1 formula computes (via an update of rank 1) the symmetric solution that is "closest" to the current approximate-value Bk".
Then, is this statement not true?

author: @chrisrycroft2010
textdisplay:
@@hyukppen Yes, I think that statement on Wikipedia is a little misleading. Any symmetric rank one update can be written as c^T c for some vector c. For a problem in R^n, then c will have n degrees of freedom, but equation (**) gives you n constraints, so it's not surprising that you get a unique solution.

I think that statement on Wikipedia is technically true, because the solution you get will be the "closest" by virtue of being the unique one. But that statement is misleading about the origins of this update formula and should probably be revised.

Furthermore, in any case, "closest" is ambiguous since that depends on the choice of norm (e.g. Frobenius norm, 2-norm).

author: @hyukppen
textdisplay: ‚Äã@@chrisrycroft2010 Thank you for your kind explanation. I agree with you.

author: @hyukppen

About your comment
"For a problem in R^n, then c will have n degrees of freedom, but equation (**) gives you n constraints, so it's not surprising that you get a unique solution."
But, in my opinion, if the equation is non-linear for the n variables, then, we can't say uniqueness, isn't it?
for example,
x^2 = 1
y^2 = 1
Two equations but 4 solutions!
and (**) is non-linear becuase if u = [x;y;z],
u*u^T = [x^2, xy, xz ; yx, y^2, yz ; zx, zy, z^2]

textdisplay: It isn't actually specified in the paper or the official implementation in PyTorch. I've simply found glorot uniform to be fairly reliable as far as initializers go. They used conditional GAN and train a semantic segmentation CNN along with an adversarial network that discriminates segmentation maps coming from the ground truth or from the segmentation network for BraTS 2017 segmentation task

author: @valentinfontanger4962
textdisplay: Hi, if you are experimenting with gans for super resolution, try to add gaussian noise between layers of your discriminator. The results are visually better and it also maximizes the psnr in validation

author: @toufiqmusah6480
textdisplay:
Great recommendation.
Do you by any input on the cycleGAN implementation? Will gaussian noise have any kind of effect in that regard?

author: @valentinfontanger4962
textdisplay:
I am not very familiar with cycleGAN in particular. But the idea behind adding gaussian noise inside the discriminator is that it prevents the training from collapsing. The idea is that, at the very beginning, the generator generates garbages, which the discriminator can easily identify. If such case, you loose the purpose of antagonist.
@@toufiqmusah6480
In short, I believe this should work for any kind of GAN architecture

author: @user-gx9hk8gt3k
textdisplay:
31:16 what does length.out = input$bins + 1 mean? Can you explain it to me in plain English? (The answer has been generated by ChatGPT.) In the Shiny app code, seq(min(x), max(x), length.out = input$bins + 1) is used to create a sequence of values that is used to define the bins for the histogram.

The seq function is used to create a sequence of evenly spaced values. In this case, the first argument min(x) is the starting value of the sequence, and the second argument max(x) is the ending value of the sequence. The length.out argument specifies the length of the sequence that should be generated.

The value of input$bins is the number of bins selected by the user using the sliderInput. The +1 is added to input$bins to ensure that the sequence has one more value than the number of bins selected by the user. This is because the hist function includes the rightmost edge of the last bin, so the number of breaks needed is bins+1.

Therefore, length.out = input$bins + 1 means that the seq function should generate a sequence of values that is input$bins + 1 long, starting at the minimum value of x and ending at the maximum value of x. This sequence of values is used to define the breaks or bins for the histogram.

textdisplay:
Hi Freddy,

I have developed a webapp using flexdashboard and shiny, i want to host it on AWS on Windows, the steps that you have showed will work for Windows too ?
I want to send an URL to my fellow team members who will be using to view the webapp(basically a dashboard), I dont want to send them an IP address as a URL instead i want to have a domain name ex: www.myshinyapp.com something like this. Any info will be very useful, I am only stuck with the hosting part of it on AWS.

Thanks
Vish

author: @freddydrennan4438
textdisplay:
You will have to connect to the AWS server differently because windows does not have a bash shell. All the steps should work except you have to ssh into AWS differently than Mac/Linux. I'm sure you can change the name of the server but I've never done that.

https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/WindowsGuide/connecting_to_windows_instance.html

This may help, but honestly, using windows for things that are inherently linux based is usually more complicated than it needs to be, IMO.

author: @vishu380
textdisplay:
Hi Freddy,
Thanks for your reply. I have installed Rstudio server on the AWS EC2 instance, I wanted to understand how to create an URL and send this URL to my Co workers so that when they click on it they should be able to see the dashboard which i have it on my rstudio server on the instance.

Thanks
Vish

author: @freddydrennan4438
textdisplay:
Hi friend! In the EC2 dashboard, there is an ip address. Use that ip address and then add the port at the end. For example, my RStudio server is at 18.217.102.18:8787

You will want to set up an elastic IP in the aws console so that if you shut down the server the ip address wont change. I have never set up a fancy url on AWS, so you'll have to look up on AWS or call someone to find out how to do that.

author: @hasnainmamdani4534
textdisplay:
Excellent resource! Really enjoyed the depth covered in this hour-long video.
On the candidate generation model: how is a simple ML model trained on users, i.e., what are the inputs and output(s) for that simple ML model?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Hello Hasnain, a simple machine learning model for candidate generation is typically trained on a dataset of user interactions with items, such as clicks, views, or purchases. The inputs to the model would be features extracted from these interactions, such as the user ID, the item ID, the timestamp of the interaction, and any other relevant contextual information. The output of the model would be a probability score for each item, indicating the likelihood that the user would be interested in that item. This probability score can then be used to rank the items and generate a list of recommended candidates for the user. Hope this helps!

author: @joelrodriguez1232
textdisplay:
Here is all the code:


library (ggplot2)
titanic = read.csv("titanic.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
View(titanic)

# set up factors.
titanic$Pclass = as.factor(titanic$Pclass)
titanic$Survived = as.factor(titanic$Survived)
titanic$Sex = as.factor(titanic$Sex )
titanic$Embarked = as.factor(titanic$Embarked )


ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Survived)) + geom_bar()
geom_bar()

prop.table(table(titanic$Survived)) #Compares who perished and who survived



#create the same plot with title
# We can use color to look at two aspects (i.e dimmensions)
ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Sex, fill = Survived))+
theme_bw() +
geom_bar() +
labs(y = "Passenger Count",
title = "Titanic Survival Rates by Sex")

# What was the survival rate bty calss of tickets
ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Pclass, fill = Survived))+
theme_bw() +
geom_bar() +
labs(y = "Passenger Count",
title = "Titanic Survival Rates by P-Class")

# 4 What was the survival Rates by class of ticket and gender?

ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Sex, fill = Survived))+
theme_bw() +
facet_wrap(~Pclass)+
geom_bar() +
labs(y = "Passenger Count",
title = "Titanic Survival Rates by P-Class and sex")


# 5th What os the distribution of passenger ages?

ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Age)) +
theme_bw() +
geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) +
labs(y = "Passenger Count",
x = "age (binwidth = 5)",
title = "Titanic Age Distribution")



# 6th question - What are the survival rates by age?

ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Age, fill = Survived)) +
theme_bw() +
geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) +
labs(y = "Passenger Count",
x = "age (binwidth = 5)",
title = "Titanic Age Distribution")
#boxplot is another way of visualization

ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Survived, y = Age)) +
theme_bw() +
geom_boxplot()+
labs(x = "Age",
y = "Survived",
title = "Titanic Age Distribution")
#use Facets for density plots
ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Age, fill = Survived )) +
theme_bw() +
facet_wrap(Sex ~ Pclass) +
geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
labs(x = "Age",
y = "Survived",
title = "Titanic Age Distribution")

# you can tell the same story with a Histogram
ggplot(titanic,aes(x = Age, fill = Survived )) +
theme_bw() +
facet_wrap(Sex ~ Pclass) +
geom_histogram(binwidth = 5) +
labs(x = "Age",
y = "Survived",
title = "Titanic Age Distribution")

textdisplay: Hi I asked a similar question. author: @jagatjeebanbasantia4957
textdisplay: how to create a 2D hex bin plot Using jointplot

author: @edurekaIN
textdisplay:
Please follow this to create a 2D hex bin plot:
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
sns.set(style=""ticks"")

rs = np.random.RandomState(11)
x = rs.gamma(2, size=1000)
y = -.5 * x + rs.normal(size=1000)

sns.jointplot(x, y, kind=""hex"", color=""#4CB391"").

author: @StephanKoehler
textdisplay:
Simply awesome ... very clear, top-level explanation and excellent examples. I however did have some trouble with the VegaLite package:

vega = folium.features.VegaLite(sw_bar, width='100%', height='100%')
NameError: name 'sw_bar' is not defined

author: @RyanNoonan
textdisplay:
Thanks.

altair/VegaLite can be tricky however the error message seems to indicate that the cell with sw_bar has not been run possibly because the package(s) have not been completely installed. I cannot tell you exactly how to fix but I can give some tips to help. Make sure altair and vega have been installed. You may need to use jupyter nbextension enable or install... in the terminal with vega. Check your renderer (altair.renderers.enable...). Check the altair documentation for details on nbextension and renderers. I use the anaconda package environment to manage the packages. After everything is installed and set-up - you may need to close everything and restart/reopen, etc.

author: @StephanKoehler
textdisplay:
@@RyanNoonan Thanks for that clarification and making the effort. I think closing down and re-running resolved this issue for me.

What I personally would really appreciate is another clear tutorial about the differences between matplotlib, folium, plotly and leaflet, with some examples of where each of them shine to help guid me through the library zoo. At this point I've gone with folium, in part thanks to your very clear video, but feel that perhaps plotly would be the more powerful and "most up-to-date".

author: @amiliavachford183
textdisplay:
thanks for useful video
If anybody have a problem with calculating the mean of Type 1 grouped data, use this:
df= pd.read_csv('modified.csv')
df.groupby(['Type 1']).mean(numeric_only=True)
instand of this:
df= pd.read_csv('modified.csv')
df.groupby(['Type 1']).mean()
That way, it won't include string-type data in the mean and sum functions.

author: @brinker180
textdisplay:
This video was super helpful, thank you Keith!

In case anyone gets to the end of this video, around 48:00, Keith talks about the groupby operator and starts to go over the section "Aggregate Statistic using Groupby (Sum, Mean Counting)". You might run into errors due something that changed after Pandas version 2.0.0.

Instead of writing: df.groupby(["Type 1"]).mean()
Try writing: df.groupby(["Type 1"]).mean(numeric_only=True)

After version 2.0.0 the numeric_only value was changed to False versus True as it's default, causing errors such as "can not convert strings". Hope this is helpful, have a good one!

author: @prathamdave5849
textdisplay:
"Assignment Question Answer":

from collections import Counter

smt = df['Cuisines']
smt.dropna(inplace=True)
cusinevals = smt.values.tolist()
finallist = []
for cusine in cusinevals:
for val in cusine.split(','):
finallist.append(val.strip())

print(Counter(finallist).most_common(5))

(Note that directly querying it wont work because Cuisines contains comma separated values)

author: @ludd8489
textdisplay: At 10:11, I don't understand why he is saying that when you associate red (so negative) weights with the surrounding pixels, "the sum is largest when those middle pixels are bright, but the surrounding pixels are darker". If red pixels are negative weights shouldn't it be the opposite?

author: @LinhNguyen-nh8oq
textdisplay: The way I think about this is that the larger the sum, the more likely the pattern. So basically, It made the decision on how much percent the pattern appear base on previous input. And in the process of making a decision, neurons which have the most weight is the most important input in making a decision. So the more green the weight is, the more important of the neuron in the process of determing the percent. And reverse for red weight. So back to your question, we want to identify the edge pattern(which is a white line and the surrounding will be black pixel), so the middle pixel have to be the brightest and the surrounding will be darkest. Hope this helps you

author: @pazman6856
textdisplay: If someone could please explain. I‚Äôm just beginning to try and understand this stuff. How can this process be entirely linear? Essentially each layer is some linear combination of the previous layer. But surely the theory described in the video of edges combining to form shapes, require the shape layer to be dependent not on a linear combination of the ‚Äúedges‚Äù in the previous layer, but instead the relationship between the edges. For an example, looking at the circular shape in a 9, the right circular edge of the second layer should only count for anything in the third layer, if there is also some sort of connection to the right edge (represented in the second layer) present. Hence, surely this could be more accurately represented by a multiplication of the two second layer neurons instead of a linear combination of them?

author: @drewarnold6741
textdisplay: Digital neural networks are not and will not be part of any type of general intelligence. Intelligence is not stored data and an architecture to relate and access it. Look at it this way... a person is not "intelligent" because of basic network wiring in their brain. Rather their intelligence stems from two cells (egg and sperm) which propagate and self assemble into a complex organism that it self can observe and manipulate the world around it. That is intelligence. We are so far off from creating something like that and touting that a "neural network" is a key component or accelerator to general AI is pure fantasy.

author: @williamli1047
textdisplay:
For those who watch this video years after it posted. I think a few things are changed:
1) you do not need to download the web driver anymore. Just use
driver = webdriver.Chrome()
2) if you open a page and it closes immediately, add the following (assuming you are using Chrome as well):
from selenium.webdriver.chrome.options import Options
options = Options()
options.add_experimental_option("detach", True)
driver = webdriver.Chrome(options= options)
These are two main issues I had when I was coding along. Took me sometime to figure out a solution. Hope it helps.

textdisplay:
If the selenium version you are using is v4.6.0 or above (which I think it is as I see SeleniumManger in the error trace), then you don't really have to set the driver.exe path. Selenium can handle the browser and drivers by itself.

So your code can be simplified as below:

from selenium import webdriver

driver = webdriver.Chrome()

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Ah, when viewing the source, it only includes the first 8 urls that are tagged. Others are not tagged in some way, from having a quick look at the source.
What you could do (although might not be the most elegant solution) is read in all your html as a single string and then use a substring match to extract all urls containing 'https://www.reddit.com/r/politics/comments/'

source <- "https://www.reddit.com/r/politics/new/"
html <- paste(readLines(source), collapse="\n")
# Extract all urls, so substrings containing 'https://www.reddit.com/r/politics/comments'


Rebecca

author: @sebastianbirk9357
textdisplay:
1:21:24: The binary cross-entropy loss formula is missing a minus and parentheses at the beginning and end. When the "jump" from likelihood function to loss function is done, the minus should be added. It then magically reappears in the cost function at 1:22:07 instead.

There are also some inconsistencies in notation at 1:17:05. While the bottom equation is the likelihood that should be maximized (probability of y given X, theta), the top equation is not the likelihood but instead the probability that the model gives for all examples being of class 1 (probability for y=1 given X, theta). These two equations are not equal. The bottom equation is then correctly used as part of the maximum likeliihood estimation.

textdisplay:
"Hi, you got the right answer. Kudos.
The contest is over and winners have been announced in our community and also mentioned in the top comment of the video as well. Thanks for your participation.

The correct answer to the quiz is Option B.
Explanation:
In a neural network, the error in the model is always calculated after finding the predicted output, i.e., at the output layer of the network.This predicted output is compared with the actual output of the model. The backpropagation algorithm is performed on the network, and the weights are optimized to reduce the error in the model. This process is repeated multiple times to get the final output, which has the least minimum error.
"

author: @edurekaIN
textdisplay:
1. The autoencoder architecture essentially learns an ‚Äúidentity‚Äù function. It will take the input data, create a compressed representation of the core / primary driving features of that data and then learn to reconstruct it again.
2.You will need to unzip them and combine them into a single data.

author: @shubhampoddar9158
textdisplay: how does dimensionality reduction take place through encoder?

author: @edurekaIN
textdisplay: Autoencoders are trained using both encoder and decoder section, but after training then only the encoder is used, and the decoder is trashed. So, if you want to obtain the dimensionality reduction you have to set the layer between encoder and decoder of a dimension lower than the input's one.

author: @vast634
textdisplay: Important detail when trying to transfer from a simulation to the real world: make the simulation have many random variations in its behavior/mechanics during runtime. (such as drag, gravity, friction, size of the agent, random perturbations, etc) This will make the agent have to generalize more, and not over optimize on the details in the sim. This makes it easier to transfer the agents capabilities to a real world environment.

author: @Eric-zo8wo
textdisplay:
0:41: üìö This class will cover linear regression, batch and stochastic gradient descent, and the normal equations as algorithms for fitting linear regression models.
5:35: üè† The speaker discusses using multiple input features, such as size and number of bedrooms, to estimate the size of a house.
12:03: üìù The hypothesis is defined as the sum of features multiplied by parameters.
18:40: üìâ Gradient descent is a method to minimize a function J of Theta by iteratively updating the values of Theta.
24:21: üìù Gradient descent is a method used to update values in each step by calculating the partial derivative of the cost function.
30:13: üìù The partial derivative of a term with respect to Theta J is equal to XJ, and one step of gradient descent updates Theta J
36:08: üîë The choice of learning rate in the algorithm affects its convergence to the global minimum.
41:45: üìä Batch gradient descent is a method in machine learning where the entire training set is processed as one batch, but it has a disadvantage when dealing with large datasets.
47:13: üìà Stochastic gradient descent allows for faster progress in large datasets but never fully converges.
52:23: üìù Gradient descent is an iterative algorithm used to find the global optimum, but for linear regression, the normal equation can be used to directly jump to the global optimum.
58:59: üìù The derivative of a matrix function with respect to the matrix itself is a matrix with the same dimensions, where each element is the derivative with respect to the corresponding element in the original matrix.
1:05:51: üìù The speaker discusses properties of matrix traces and their derivatives.
1:13:17: üìù The derivative of the function is equal to one-half times the derivative of Theta multiplied by the transpose of X minus the transpose of y.
Recap by Tammy AI

textdisplay: 28:51, what is x0 and x1? If we have a single feature, say # of bedrooms, how can we have x0 and x1? Wouldn't x0 be just nothing? I'm confused. author: @MahakYadav12
textdisplay: The value of x0 is always one 1.  So theta0 can rely on x0 for the update. If we have  single feature  then h(X) =x0*Theta0 + x1* theta1 (which is ultimately equal to theta0 + x1*theta1 as x0=1,  theta0 can also be referred as intercept and theta1 as slope  if you compare it with the equation of a straight line  such that price of house is linear function of  # of bedrooms)

author: @theMiaow
textdisplay:
Precision -> it focuses more on the quality aspect in how the model actually predicted true positives in a significant amount. Thus, higher precision results in lower false positive rates.

Recall -> it focuses more on the quantity of positive INSTANCES (both false and true positives are included) that were identified by the model. Thus, higher recall results in lower false negative rates.

author: @ofirbarg
textdisplay: Should not Precision be described as avoids a lot of mistakes in predicting bananas or apples (not and)?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello, precision is a measure used in statistics and machine learning to describe the accuracy of a model or classifier. It is defined as the ratio of true positive predictions to the total number of positive predictions made by the model.

In the context of predicting bananas or apples, precision would represent the proportion of correct positive predictions made by the model, out of all the positive predictions it made. Precision focuses on the accuracy of positive predictions and is calculated as:

Precision = True Positives / (True Positives + False Positives)

Therefore, precision does not specifically capture the avoidance of mistakes in predicting only bananas or apples. It quantifies the correctness of positive predictions in general, without explicitly distinguishing between bananas and apples.

To provide a more specific description related to avoiding mistakes in predicting bananas or apples, other metrics such as recall or accuracy might be more suitable. Recall, for example, measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive instances out of all the actual positive instances in the dataset. Accuracy, on the other hand, represents the overall correctness of predictions, taking into account both positive and negative instances.

textdisplay:
0:28: üìö The video discusses supervised learning, specifically linear regression, locally weighted regression, and logistic regression.
5:38: üìö Locally weighted regression is a non-parametric learning algorithm that requires keeping data in computer memory.
13:05: üìä Locally weighted regression is a method that assigns different weights to data points based on their distance from the prediction point.
19:01: üìö Locally linear regression is a learning algorithm that may not have good results and is not great at extrapolation.
24:46: üîç The video discusses Gaussian density and its application in determining housing prices.
31:31: üí° The likelihood of the parameters is the probability of the data given the parameters, assuming independent and identically distributed errors.
36:55: üìä Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE) is a commonly used method in statistics to estimate parameters by maximizing the likelihood or log-likelihood of the data.
43:44: üìä Applying linear regression to a binary classification problem is not a good idea.
49:22: üéØ The video discusses the choice of hypothesis function in learning algorithms and why logistic regression is chosen as a special case of generalized linear models.
54:45: üìö The video explains how to compress two equations into one line using a notational trick.
1:01:31: ‚úè Batch gradient ascent is used to update the parameters in logistic regression.
1:07:52: üìö The video explains how to use Newton's method to find the maximum or minimum of a function.
1:13:55: üí° Newton's method is a fast algorithm for finding the place where the first derivative of a function is 0, using the first and second derivatives.

textdisplay:
32:18 I have a question about this likelihood function. Can somebody help me with it?

According to the IID assumption, the probability of all the observations is equal to the product of each probability . However, isn‚Äôt the expression a density instead of a probability of a normal distribution? I am really confused. I think the probability should be the integral of density function. author: @HamzaAsgharKhan
textdisplay: For I.I.D, P(AB) = P(A)P(B). Your observation about it being the probability density of the Gaussian is correct. When we maximize it, we are trying to find the point which has the highest probability. A point that has the highest density will have the highest probability. So using the probability density function is correct in that regard (I think you are confused by the fact that the density will probably result in a value that is not between 0 and 1 but with a little thought about what I said, hopefully you will be able to see why normalizing the values to be between 0 and 1 do not really matter). I don't know how much help this answer will be to you, I'm simply having a hard time to articulate what I'm trying to say.

author: @liketheblue5082
textdisplay: @@HamzaAsgharKhan Thank you very much! I didn't expect someone would give me such a detailed answer! That's exactly what I thought. The product of density might not really have a meaning in statistics, the density can also be greater than 1 , but it would be enough to find the maximum point. I appreciate it!!

textdisplay:
"Hi, you got the right answer. Kudos.
The contest is over and winners have been announced in our community and also mentioned in the top comment of the video as well. Thanks for your participation.

The correct answer to the quiz is Option B.
Explanation:
In a neural network, the error in the model is always calculated after finding the predicted output, i.e., at the output layer of the network.This predicted output is compared with the actual output of the model. The backpropagation algorithm is performed on the network, and the weights are optimized to reduce the error in the model. This process is repeated multiple times to get the final output, which has the least minimum error.
"

textdisplay: At 10:11, I don't understand why he is saying that when you associate red (so negative) weights with the surrounding pixels, "the sum is largest when those middle pixels are bright, but the surrounding pixels are darker". author: @LinhNguyen-nh8oq
textdisplay: The way I think about this is that the larger the sum, the more likely the pattern. So basically, It made the decision on how much percent the pattern appear base on previous input. And in the process of making a decision, neurons which have the most weight is the most important input in making a decision. So the more green the weight is, the more important of the neuron in the process of determing the percent. And reverse for red weight. So back to your question, we want to identify the edge pattern(which is a white line and the surrounding will be black pixel), so the middle pixel have to be the brightest and the surrounding will be darkest. Hope this helps you

author: @drewarnold6741
textdisplay: Digital neural networks are not and will not be part of any type of general intelligence. Intelligence is not stored data and an architecture to relate and access it. Look at it this way... a person is not "intelligent" because of basic network wiring in their brain. Rather their intelligence stems from two cells (egg and sperm) which propagate and self assemble into a complex organism that it self can observe and manipulate the world around it. That is intelligence. We are so far off from creating something like that and touting that a "neural network" is a key component or accelerator to general AI is pure fantasy.

author: @awaisahmadsiddiqi6505
textdisplay: can someone please explain at @26:22 , how 3 feature maps are formed in convolution when there is only one input image?

author: @AAmini
textdisplay: Depending on how many convolutional filters are in your layer you can learn an arbitrary number of feature maps. So in this layer we hav learned three convolutional filters, each filter outputs one feature map, thus we have a total of three output feature maps. Recall that the convolution operation typically takes as input at least two arguments (1) the filter size and (2) the number of filters; the number of outputs and size of the outputs is directly dependent on these two arguments.

author: @rustycherkas8229
textdisplay:
"Impressive"? Or frightening?
This appears to be the beginning of the transition from "A.I. tools" used by humans to the potentially active embodiment of "our way of thinking."
Several researchers have expressed the POV that brains (minds?) train, store and refine a "latent space" that is shaped by moment to moment sensory input (and internal influences such as brain chemistry). "Reality" is individual, based on the feedback (effects) from an individual's unique experiences shaping/refining their mind's notion of "present" and, drawing on its stored catalog of (usually self-serving) strategies and projections, seeking to influence what might be possible in the moments ahead. The shape-shifting fluidity of various Julia sets transforming from one to another seems to be an analog of this explanation of the generator's concept of a generic "cat" object... Every individual has an idiomatic representation of "cat" in their mind that may be 'mostly' recognisable but always distinct from every other individual's representation of "cat".
I am both impressed and somewhat concerned. Like the stars being too far to reach, at least knowing the orders of magnitude separating a single brain's synapses and the comparatively paltry number of interconnects in a NN will help me get to sleep tonight. Take your time, boys...

author: @tiro0oO5
textdisplay: first off: great podcast and amazing quest. This was super interesting. ... but a critical question: at 51:27 she does not really answer the question. I think it should be mentioned much more under which conditions the advesarial attacks actually work. White box attacks are very limited in application. And I read the Tencent paper on their "Tesla hack" and it was basically on a parking lot without many markers and they draw their own markers. Their conclusion was that this could "drive the vehicle in the opposing lane" completely ignoring the fact that if there are vehicles in the opposing lane, they get detected, etc. etc. ... In addition it is not a vision only system, but has additional map information, but that is a different story. ... my general feel is still that adveserial attacks are super interesting, but not feasible "in the wild" and more importantly not proofen to work "in the wild". And her answer did nothing, but strengthen me in this believe. It sounded to me that she wanted to defend her field, but had no arguments for it. ... So if anyone has something to add to this point, I am super curious. Kind greetings :)

author: @engkamyabi
textdisplay:
With all respect and while agree with most of the video but I think ensuring of data quality (by checking label definitions for example) is more of a Data Science task. Automating it in a repeatable and systematic way is certainly in the MLOps realm.
This video mainly looks at MLOps from a Data Science perspective and maybe a Software/Data Engineering perspective (with Data Science in mind) is closer to what MLOps is all about because no matter how much hardcore mathematics it uses, at the end of the day it's data + code that needs to be maintained like any other data/software project (with the addition of complexities such as iterations, lineage, etc. that comes with ML.) Admittedly I'm an MLE with a SDE/DevOps background. I learned very good insights from the video, thank you for that. Andrew is one of my favorite instructors.

author: @emmanuelpoirier4602
textdisplay:
wine makers and beer brewers would be very angry if you use just those 2 parameters to determine if a drink is beer or wine:

you can find beers of all colors in the IPA / home made brewing scene, same for wine.

And I suppose alcohol content can also be quite similar due to the experience of those people.

It's important for machine learning developers to know deeply what the men on the trenches do and why, to create accurate data sampling with way more parameters, either we could end up with a tasteless, oversimplified, all look alike, all taste alike food product range, which ultimately make people also look alike, and think alike.

That's something we can actually observe in reality with a long track record of the food evolution.

author: @Deeplearningai
textdisplay:
3:20- 10:45 speaker introduction and their thoughts on MLOps
10:55 - 20:41 Machine Learning Operations or ‚ÄúMLOps‚Äù for short, is really a nascent field. People might have seen some of the articles that are out there comparing and contrasting ML and DevOps and suggesting that MLOps is sort of a mashup of the two. Is that the right way to think about it? And to what extent do the roles of Data Scientist or ML Engineer involve MLOps?
20:54- 24:55 How is MLOps actually implemented in an industry setting? Is there some kind of a framework people use?
25:04 - 29:57 Is MLOps suitable for early-stage startups, or only for teams with enough resources to essentially do what the big tech companies do? Do you invent your own tools?
30:03- 34:54 Chip, you've written a post that captured all the tools out there, and what are some of the trends. I'd like to get your perspective on this.
34:56- 44:21 Apart from taking courses, what are some of the other resources or activities that you might recommend to learners interested in gaining practical experience with MLOps?
44:47- 48:12 A question about "Experiment Tracking": ‚ÄúI understood that the MLOps pipeline needs to be data-centric, not model-centric, but when it comes to the experiments tracking (models that might not have been deployed) do we really need an application or framework? Don't you think that we need to address this requirement in an MLOps infrastructure‚Äù?
48:15- In the introduction to machine learning in production, we talk about the compromise between an ML Engineer and a business owner regarding the goals of an ML deployment (test set accuracy vs revenue). However, how should we educate the industrial management regarding the machine learning cycle? How to tell them the resources they are very motivated to invest in might not give them the result?
52:15- 54:56 MLE is much more than algorithms/models. What other tech skills should one have to be considered as a good MLE? say some backend engineer skill sets?
55:01-56:44 Almost all job profiles require many years of work experience to become an MLOps engineer, so where should future MLOps engineer should start in his/her career?
56:50 -1:03:12 ML Ops tools come and go. What are some important principles of ML ops that will remain relevant 5 years down the road that are tool agnostic?
1:03:55 - 1:09:18 Course 3 demo by Robert Crowe

author: @willd1mindmind639
textdisplay: The future is basically more industry normalization around certain conventions and models within AI that will allow for a large amount of infrastructure, products and services that companies can use for their own AI solutions in the cloud (and off).   Which is cool because a lot of corporations are still tepid about taking the leap fully into AI for various reasons, especially related to cost and risk.   By having industry standard frameworks that provide portability for IA solutions and infrastructure and platforms as a service in the cloud for running those solutions at scale you can help ease some of the burden.   It will not address all of the reasons for slow adoption of AI as a whole across the board but make it more appealing for those kinds of applications that can most benefit.   The only downside to this in the long term is if there is no big payoff in such industry adoption of those common frameworks and models as attitudes change, economic justification changes and other real world factors affect changes towards AI.   Meaning that it could potentially lead to another kind of AI winter if those platforms and services don't take off providing justification for further R&D and investment which already is mostly concentrated among large big data and silicon valley corporations.

textdisplay:
I would like to use "ggplot2" to create a graph showing whether life satisfaction returns to the value it had before the unemployment event occurred.
Unemployment I have coded with 0 = not unemployed and 1 = unemployed. General life satisfaction is coded 0 - 10.

I have already created the data set df_emp with a subset command, which contains all persons who were unemployed at least once. It also contains all years of observation of these persons. So all years before, during and after unemployment, as well as the corresponding values for life satisfaction

The years before, during and after the event should now be entered on the x-axis. Where 0 is the event unemployment. The values -1 -2 and 1 2 etc. show values for the years before and after unemployment.
On the y-axis the values for life satisfaction should then be deducted (centered).

Unfortunately, I can't manage to model this graphic in R and would therefore be very pleased if somebody could help me or give me some tips on how to proceed.

Best regards

ps. I got the graphic from Lucas et al. (2004) - Unemployment alters the set point for life satisfaction

author: @vikrantl1824
textdisplay: Hi Guru, I would like to request for pointers for AB testing where the buyer might do a frequency capping or throttling, thanks

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hi Vikrant! Here are a few pointers to avoid the problem of frequency capping or throttling in A/B testing:
¬†
Use a randomization method to ensure that each variation is shown to a similar number of visitors. Use different variations of the website for different segments of the audience. For example, you could use a different variation for new visitors and a different variation for returning visitors. Use software that allows you to cap the frequency of how many times visitors are shown a variation, by setting a limit on how many times a visitor can see a variation before being excluded from the test.

Let us know if this helps you to get more accurate results and avoid the problem of frequency capping or throttling.

author: @sandraoriji8351
textdisplay: In the Bonus Round - Scaling Up, why is fit_models[stock_line] = m instead of fit_models[stock_line] = model

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Hello Sandra, the purpose of this line is simply to construct a dictionary to store instances of the model. Later on, we generate future predictions from these stored instances. It's important to note that 'model' is merely a variable. Also, in step 5 above, we utilize the originally instantiated model 'm' to make future predictions. An alternative approach is to simply use 'm.fit(frame)' without assigning it to any variable, and this will also function effectively.

author: @sandraoriji8351
textdisplay: Hello, I tried this on another dataset but i am a little confused. Before creating my model using Prophet my data shape was 3201 rows but after fitting the model m.fit(df), the shape reduced to 1203, and my period is period = 365 and freq = 'D'. But when I plot my predicted data the 365 days added can be seen. Is this normal? From the video, the shape of your data decreased after fitting.

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Hello Sandra, when it comes to the original dataframe, our procedure involves isolating each time series by the 'Store/Product' column before fitting the model. This isolation process reduces the dataframe size for each 'Store/Product,' (frame) as illustrated in the tutorial. Now, if you are referring to the 'future' dataframe generated from the fitted model, its length depends on the value set for the 'periods' attribute. In other words, the more periods you specify, the more extensive the forecast will be, leading to an increase in the size of the dataframe.

author: @sandraoriji8351
textdisplay: @@Datasciencedojo Yeah I understand that. My data is about regional sales. The region has 4 unique value. Of which I filtered just one of the region for forecasting as shown in the video. After filtering the shape was 3201 for only one region filtered. For the period I used 365 and freq 'D'. So after fitting the model, the shape reduced and I don't know why. The shape should be 3201 + 365 but when I checked it was 1201. So my question is what went wrong or is it normal? Also, when I plotted the predicted value the additional one year(365) can be seen from the plot.

author: @sandraoriji8351
textdisplay: Awesome Video, but I have a question. Why do you have to filter the dataframe (frame) to build the model? Why no use the whole dataset (df) to build the model. Is there a specific reason?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Hello Sandra, the reason for filtering the dataframe (frame) when building a time series model is to isolate each time-series data and capture its individual time-dependent patterns, ensuring accurate forecasting for each time series. Using the entire dataset (df) would mix these patterns, making it difficult for the model to provide store/product-specific predictions.

author: @user-xs9xl5mn4o
textdisplay: great video , how can we send a small dataset in request insted of single rows?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello, there are several ways to send a small dataset in a request instead of sending single rows. Here are a few options:

1. Use a JSON array: You can create a JSON array containing all the rows of your dataset and send it as the payload of your request. The server can then parse the JSON array and process the data accordingly.
2. Use a CSV or TSV file: You can create a CSV or TSV file containing all the rows of your dataset and send it as the payload of your request. The server can then parse the file and process the data accordingly.
3. Use a compressed archive file: You can create a compressed archive file (such as a ZIP file) containing all the rows of your dataset and send it as the payload of your request. The server can then decompress the file and process the data accordingly.
4. Use a database connection: If the dataset is stored in a database, you can establish a database connection from your application and send a query to retrieve the data. This way, you can send the entire dataset in a single request.

The choice of method will depend on your specific use case and the requirements of your application.

author: @sarthak7413
textdisplay: How can we define as json input and output in service.api call?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello Sarthak, JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight data interchange format that is widely used in web services and APIs for data exchange. When making an API call, you can use JSON as both input and output format. Here's how you can define JSON input and output in a service API call:

JSON Input:
To define JSON input in a service API call, you need to send a JSON object as the request payload. The JSON object should contain the input data for the API call. Here's an example of how to define JSON input in a service API call using Python:

import requests
import json

url = "http://example.com/api"
data = {
"name": "John",
"age": 30,
"email": "john@example.com"
}
headers = {"Content-Type": "application/json"}

response = requests.post(url, headers=headers, data=json.dumps(data))

In this example, we define a Python dictionary containing the input data as a JSON object. We then use the json.dumps() method to convert the dictionary to a JSON string and send it as the request payload.

JSON Output:
To define JSON output in a service API call, the API should return a JSON object as the response payload. The JSON object should contain the output data for the API call. Here's an example of how to define JSON output in a service API call using Python:

import requests
import json

url = "http://example.com/api"
headers = {"Accept": "application/json"}

response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)
data = json.loads(response.content)

In this example, we set the Accept header to application/json to indicate that we want to receive a JSON response. We then use the json.loads() method to convert the JSON string in the response content to a Python dictionary. This dictionary contains the output data for the API call.

author: @sarthak7413
textdisplay: How can we define CI/CD pipeline in jenkins using BentoML?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
BentoML is a popular open-source platform for packaging and deploying machine learning models. To define a CI/CD pipeline for a BentoML project in Jenkins, you can follow these steps:

Install and configure Jenkins on your system.
Create a Jenkins job for your BentoML project.
Configure the job to use a version control system (such as Git) for the source code.
Set up a Jenkinsfile for your project. The Jenkinsfile defines the build, test, and deployment steps for your project.
Use BentoML's CLI to build, test, and deploy your model as part of the Jenkins pipeline.
Here's an example Jenkinsfile that uses BentoML to build, test, and deploy a model:

pipeline {
agent any
stages {
stage('Build') {
steps {
sh 'pip install bentoml'
sh 'bentoml build .'
}
}
stage('Test') {
steps {
sh 'bentoml serve-gunicorn . --port=5000 &'
sh 'bentoml test . --concurrency=10'
sh 'killall gunicorn'
}
}
stage('Deploy') {
steps {
sh 'bentoml deploy . --platform=local --port=5000'

This Jenkinsfile has three stages:

Build: This stage installs BentoML and builds the BentoML bundle for the project.
Test: This stage starts a BentoML server, runs tests against the server, and stops the server.
Deploy: This stage deploys the BentoML service to a local platform.
You can customize the Jenkinsfile to suit your specific needs, such as deploying to a different platform or running more tests. Once you've defined the pipeline, Jenkins will automatically build, test, and deploy your BentoML project whenever changes are made to the source code.

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: @@sarthak7413 You're right, the example Jenkinsfile I provided does not include a step to containerize the BentoML service into a Docker image. To add this step to the pipeline, you can use the bentoml containerize command, which generates a Docker image from the BentoML service bundle.

author: @santhoshravindrabharathy618
textdisplay: Can you create dashboards with automatically updating data on Tableau?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Yes, you can create dashboards with automatically updating data on Tableau. To do this, you can use the "Live" connection option when connecting to your data source. This will allow Tableau to refresh the data in the dashboard whenever the underlying data changes.

Learn more about it here: https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/create-tableau-dashboards-auto-refresh-data-source-feature-lopez?trk=read_related_article-card_title

author: @ct6858
textdisplay:
When entering the read.csv( ... ), I get the following error:

Error in make.names(col.names, unique = TRUE) :

invalid multibyte string at '<ff><fe>v'
In addition: Warning messages:
1: In read.table(file = file, header = header, sep = sep, quote = quote, :
line 1 appears to contain embedded nulls

and so on.

Anyone know why this happens? I can read other csv files

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay:
Hello Cholo, it seems like there is some sort of invalid encoding in the name of the column. There are some special characters in the column name. You would need to pass a fileencoding parameter with the encoding type UTF-8 to read.csv function
x=read.csv("filename.csv",fileEncoding = "UCS-2LE")

author: @moomoopuppy508
textdisplay: So 300 impressions could be a single person viewing a post 300 times?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Yes, that's correct! In the context of digital marketing and social media analytics, an "impression" refers to the number of times a particular piece of content (such as a post, advertisement, or video) is displayed on a user's screen. It doesn't necessarily mean that 300 unique individuals viewed the content; it could be the result of a single person viewing the content 300 times or a combination of multiple people viewing it fewer times.

author: @Blueatlasmarketing
textdisplay: I get the data, but how does the business owner dive into and then make decisions for their marketing and business goals?

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Hello, to make informed decisions for marketing and business goals, a business owner should analyze gathered data and identify trends and customer segments. Set specific and measurable goals, establish key performance indicators (KPIs), and select appropriate marketing channels. Create tailored marketing strategies, conduct A/B testing, and regularly monitor and measure campaign performance. Gather qualitative feedback from customers and iterate marketing approaches based on insights. Prioritize data security, seek professional expertise if needed, and ensure decisions align with the business's vision and objectives.

author: @Datasciencedojo
textdisplay: Hello @@jessedawson1454, you are correct. On May 1, 2022, Amazon shut down Alexa Internet which subsequently discontinued Alexa Rank with it. You can find more details here: https://www.coywolf.news/seo/amazon-alexa-rank-end-of-life/#:~:text=Alexa%20Rank%20discontinued,of%20interest%20from%20digital%20marketers.
